WHEREAS, she also led efforts to establish Pigeon Forge's Fun Time Trolley, which
now functions as Pigeon Forge Mass Transit, the third-largest rural transit system in the United
States; and
WHEREAS, under Ms. Teaster's leadership as city manager, Pigeon Forge has
sustained record growth, achieving more than $1 billion in annual revenue for eleven
consecutive years; and
WHEREAS, she also guided her city through the 2016 wildfires and the COVID-19
pandemic; and
WHEREAS, Ms. Teaster was a member of the inaugural Leadership Sevier class and
has served her community as a supporter of Pigeon Forge Schools and the Boys and Girls Club
of Pigeon Forge; she is also a former Boy Scouts den mother; and
WHEREAS, she is a member of the Tennessee City Management Association and the
International City/County Management Association; she has represented the tourism industry in
various capacities on the East Tennessee Development Districts board; and
WHEREAS, often duly recognized for her good work, Ms. Teaster is a recipient of the J.
Prichard Barnes Community Service Award and a member of both the Pigeon Forge High
School and Sevier County High School halls of fame; and
WHEREAS, her professional accolades further include the Southeast Tourism Society's
Shining Example Award and being named Tourism Leader of the Year in 1994 and Tennessee
City Management Association's City Manager of the Year in 2000; and
WHEREAS, a woman of abiding faith, Earlene Teaster is an active member of Wears
Valley First Baptist Church; and
WHEREAS, throughout her many years of service, she enjoyed the love and support of
her husband, Glen, until his passing; she is the proud mother of two sons, Steve and Phil, the
grandmother of five grandchildren, and the great-grandmother of four great-grandchildren; and
